<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Anatomy Bingo Words</h2>

<p>Many anatomy terms are 7+ letters, making them bingo candidates with the 50-point bonus. Learning these gives you an edge when you draw medical-sounding letter combinations:</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">TRACHEA</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">12 + 50 bonus</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">STERNUM</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">9 + 50 bonus</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">CRANIUM</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">11 + 50 bonus</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>TRACHEA is especially useful — it uses all common tiles (T,R,A,C,H,E,A) and scores 62 points as a bingo. STERNUM and CRANIUM both use common letter distributions you'll draw regularly.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Challenge bait:</span> Medical words like ZYMOTIC or OXYTOCIN look obscure enough that opponents often challenge them — wasting their turn under NASPA rules while your valid word stands.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">PH and XY combos:</span> Medical Latin/Greek roots often contain PH (pharmacy, phase) and XY (oxygen, pyxis). These letter combinations score well and hook into existing board words.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Plurals and extensions:</span> Many anatomy words have useful extensions: AORTA→AORTAS, TIBIA→TIBIAE/TIBIAS, FEMUR→FEMURS. Learn both singular and plural forms.</p>
  </div>
</div>

